UPDATE "Review" SET "contentEn" = $grulla$## The Banquet of Existence: The Anatomy of the King of Curses

Within the vast and often predictable structure of contemporary shonen, there exists an almost obsessive tendency to humanize evil. We search for the foundational trauma, the open wound that justifies the blaze, the "sad past" that allows us, somehow, to empathize with the monster. We want to believe that evil is a response to an external stimulus. And yet, Gege Akutami chose to hurl into the center of _Jujutsu Kaisen_ an anomaly that defies all logic of redemption: Ryomen Sukuna.

Sukuna is not a man who fell into darkness; he is the darkness that learned to walk, to cut, and, above all, to savor. He is not a villain with a thousand-year master plan to save the world from itself, nor a misunderstood martyr. He is a natural disaster with a consciousness of its own. We are speaking of a being who does not seek the world's validation, but who understands that the world is, quite simply, his playground and his personal slaughterhouse. Throughout this analysis, we will break down why Sukuna is not merely the most formidable antagonist in the work, but a philosophical representation of absolute hedonism and the solitude that perfection entails.

---

### I. The Aesthetics of Deformity: Beyond the Human

To understand Sukuna, we must first strip him of Yuji Itadori's skin. For much of the series, we saw him limited by a vessel that hated him, a cage of flesh and morality that tried to contain an ocean of malice. But Sukuna's true essence resides in his Heian Era form: a being of four arms, two faces, and a presence that distorts reality itself.

This anatomy is not a visual whim. In the world of sorcery, the body is the soul and the soul is the body. The four arms allow him to perform hand signs and incantations—the fundamental components of sorcery—without interrupting his flow of physical combat. It is maximum efficiency. While a normal sorcerer must choose between defending himself or attacking with his technique, Sukuna is an engine of perpetual motion.

But beyond the tactical advantage, his appearance is a statement of principle. Sukuna despises human limitation. His physical existence is a necessary "excess" because his will does not fit into a standard mold. He is the "artist" who needs more brushes than the natural body provides. Looking at his design, we see that Sukuna has left behind any pretense of belonging to society. He is his own society, his own god, and his own judge.

---

### II. The Gourmet's Philosophy: The World as Ingredient

What makes Sukuna truly terrifying is not his brute strength, but his perspective. His cursed technique is based on culinary concepts: _Cleave_ (Cortar) and _Dismantle_ (Desmantelar). For Sukuna, combat is not a struggle of ideals, it is a preparation. He sees his opponents not as equals, but as cuts of meat that must be filleted to see whether there is anything inside worth consuming.

This culinary hedonism is the key to his psychology. Sukuna lives for the moment, for the pleasure of the palate, for the ecstasy of a clean cut. In a world where sorcerers are driven by duty (like Nanami) or by guilt (like Itadori), Sukuna is driven by appetite. This is the purest form of freedom and, by extension, the most dangerous. You cannot reason with someone whose only goal is to satisfy a hunger that is, by definition, infinite.

Even his **Domain Expansion, Malevolent Shrine (Santuario Malévolo)**, reinforces this idea. Unlike almost any other domain seen in the series, Sukuna's has no barriers. It does not seal the enemy within a separate space. Instead, Sukuna "paints" his reality over the real world. It is an act of divine arrogance: I do not need to trap you, because there is no place in this world where you can hide from my reach. It is the shrine of a god who does not ask for worship, but who demands the sacrifice of everything that enters his radius of action.

---

### III. The Clash of Ideologies: The Vessel and the Contents

The relationship between Sukuna and Itadori is, perhaps, the most fascinating study in contrast in modern narrative. Normally, the "inner demon" trope (think of Naruto and Kurama, or Ichigo and his Hollow) ends in an uneasy truce or a heroic symbiosis. But Sukuna breaks this rule with unusual violence. He hates Itadori. Not with a respectful hatred, but with a deep disgust.

For Sukuna, Itadori represents everything he despises: self-sacrifice, concern for the "weak," and the idea that life has intrinsic value. That a "brat" with such ideals was capable of containing him was the greatest humiliation of his thousand-year existence. Sukuna did not want to cooperate with Yuji; he wanted to erase him.

When he finally manages to transfer himself into Megumi Fushiguro's body, he does not do it solely for the power of the Ten Shadows. He does it to destroy Itadori's spirit and to inhabit a body that, in its lineage and potential, is "worthy" of his majesty. By usurping Megumi, Sukuna commits the ultimate act of cruelty: he uses the face of a friend to murder all hope. It is here that we see that Sukuna does not merely seek to win, he seeks to shatter the moral structure of those around him.

---

### IV. Solitude at the Summit: Gojo Satoru vs. Ryomen Sukuna

The confrontation between Gojo and Sukuna was more than a battle of powers; it was a philosophical debate about solitude. Gojo Satoru, the "strongest" of the modern era, lived in a solitude born of isolation. He wanted others to reach him, he wanted to raise a generation that could walk by his side. His strength was a burden he tried to transform into a bridge.

Sukuna, on the contrary, embraced solitude as the natural state of excellence. For him, being at the summit means there is no one else, and that is fine. Gojo's defeat at the hands of Sukuna was not merely a matter of spatial techniques or Mahoraga's adaptations; it was the victory of absolute egotism over pedagogical altruism.

Sukuna demonstrated that his capacity for learning is his most lethal weapon. He is not a static being. Despite being a thousand years old, Sukuna remains a student of sorcery, analyzing and stealing concepts even in the midst of the most intense fight of his life. His victory over Gojo's "Infinity" was a poem to his tactical genius: he cut the world itself to reach the one who could not be touched. In that moment, Sukuna rose above the category of "curse" to become a fundamental law of the universe.

---

### V. The Love of Calamity

One of Sukuna's strangest and most profound dialogues occurs during his encounters with Yorozu and, later, after Gojo's fall. There is talk of "love" and of how the strongest is the one who must teach others what love is. For Sukuna, love is not affection or care; it is recognition.

He "loves" his opponents to the degree that they manage to entertain him. His way of giving affection is to give them a dignified death, a death that proves that, for a brief instant, they were capable of reflecting a fraction of his light. It is a predatory love. Like a lion that respects the prey that runs faster, Sukuna recognizes the worth of those who challenge him, but that does not stop him from devouring them.

This perspective shows us that Sukuna is not a nihilist. He values strength, technique, and will. What he despises is the weakness that disguises itself as morality. For him, the only sin is to be boring or to limit oneself out of fear of the judgment of others.

---

### VI. The Legacy of the Heian Era in the Present

As the manga advances toward its climax, we see a Sukuna who has transcended even his own limits. His battle against the entire Tokyo sorcery school is not a struggle for survival, it is a final banquet. Each time he seems to be against the ropes, Sukuna reveals a new layer of his understanding of cursed energy.

He is the reminder that sorcery, at its root, is an individualistic and egotistical act. While the protagonists try to win through coordinated strategy and mutual sacrifice, Sukuna wins because his "self" is denser and heavier than the combined will of all his enemies.

There is no possible redemption for Sukuna because he does not believe he has done anything wrong. There is no "peace plan" behind his actions. If Sukuna wins, the world will simply go on existing under his whim until he grows bored and decides to turn out the lights. He is the ultimate representation of chaos that needs no justification.

---

### Conclusion: The Throne No One Can Occupy

Ryomen Sukuna remains a pillar of Gege Akutami's narrative because he is honest. He is a villain who does not lie about his intentions nor seek sympathy. He is the embodiment of the idea that perfection is solitary and that absolute power corrupts, not because it makes you "evil," but because it makes you "alien."

He is the mirror in which the insecurities of all the other characters are reflected. Before Sukuna, everyone must ask themselves: "What am I when everything I love is taken from me?" Sukuna already has the answer for himself: he is the cut, he is the fire, he is the hunger. And as long as there is something to cut or something to burn, the King of Curses will remain seated upon his throne of bones, awaiting the next dish of a banquet that never ends.

In a genre that often fears to let evil simply be evil, Sukuna is a breath of fresh and terrifying air. He is the proof that, sometimes, the monster has no mask to remove; beneath the skin, there are only more teeth.$grulla$, "titleEn" = $grulla$Ryomen Sukuna: The Empty Throne of Malevolent Perfection$grulla$ WHERE id = 'cmnn879ud001rcnde14drkkb9';
